QWidget already has quite a mess of different parent functions, is there any way to shoehorn this into existing logic? 

logicalParentWidget is not very descriptive, does this match more with the transientParentWidget name perhaps?

Patch Set 2:

Removing myself to clean up my own dashboard. If needed, add me back when work continues.
Removed reviewer Richard Moe Gustavsen.
Removed reviewer Gabriel de Dietrich (DO NOT ADD TO REVIEWS).

Patch Set 2:

(2 comments)

I had some draft comments of this. Posting in case someone wants to pick it up. It fixes a quite serious bug and is in my opinion the only thing that needs to be fixed before Qt can start defaulting to wayland on gnome-shell distros.

Patch Set 2:

This patch does fix QTBUG-68636 .

For me, perhaps visualParentWidget() name is a bit better than logicalParentWidget(). nativeParentWidget() is not only like the doc said as following

 Returns the native parent for this widget, i.e. the next ancestor widget that has a system identifier, or nullptr if it does not have any native parent

https://doc.qt.io/qt-6/qwidget.html#nativeParentWidget

it also works as a visualParentWidget() in a few cases in qwidget.cpp.

I haven't checked how the whole story works in qtwayland world yet.

Patch Set 2:

This will not solve the fundamental problem, not just the menu control, all the places where QWidget::mapToGlobal needs to be used may produce exceptions, such as QToolTip::showText. This is the design of the wayland platform, and the application should understand it, and You can try to solve these problems yourself, such as setting a parent control for QMenu. Of course, doing so may cause program developers not to care about the design of Wayland. If you must solve this problem in the Qt library, please consider more controls, not only QMenu, but also controls in QToolTip and QtQuick!
Removed reviewer Volker Hilsheimer.

Patch Set 2:

After checking more about QTBUG-68636 issue, I think I understand the issue more clear now.

The parentless QMenu, like the code in main.cpp, could be a top level window and be focused in some situation, for example, with the GNOME wayland compositor. Then we need to know which widget or the top level window triggers it. Then in Wayland, we can use those informaiton to position this QMenu correctly.

For QWindow, we have a transientParent() for this kind of purpose.

But for QMenu through QWidgetWindow, we miss it when the QMenu is parentless. That's the main reason why Johan made change about two years ago.

It should not be related with Qt Quick, all items belong to a QWindow, and the popup window or similar should have a transientParent() there already.

I have a patch for this issue, https://codereview.qt-project.org/c/qt/qtbase/+/383091

> Before looking at the code review I'm curious, what is the difference to symLinkTarget ?

symLinkTarget() is always an absolute path; it resolves any relative path relative to the directory the symlink is in.  The new method returns the raw symlink.  So, given:

$ cd /foo/bar
$ ln -s /foo/cat/baz/bing ../cat/baz/bong .
$ ls -l
 lrwxrwxrwx 1   me mine   17 Sep 29  2021 bing -> /foo/cat/baz/bing
 lrwxrwxrwx 1   me mine   15 Sep 29  2021 bong -> ../cat/baz/bong

symLinkTarget("bong") returns "/foo/cat/baz/bong" (or possibly "/foo/bar/../cat/baz/bong", not sure if it cleans the path) but the new function returns "../cat/baz/bong"; and both functions shall produce "/foo/cat/baz/bing" for symLinkTarget("bing").

> It would be great if the commit message could explain this.

Agreed.

Patch Set 1:

This is an initial implementation of a command for deploying just a single QML module.
